paragraphs.text:
%md # Zeppelin Tutorial ####*You can run any of the code within the notebook yourself by either clicking the play button (blue triangle) on the right-hand side or by pressing "Shift" + "Enter"* **Zeppelin is currently the recommended notebook for Big Data projects** Zeppelin is a web based notebook that enables interactive data analysis. It supports a wide array of programming languages such as Python, Scala, SparkSQL, shell, and markdown and can be used to implement data processing backends like Spark, Hive, etc. Each notebook contains one or more cells (also referred to as sections or paragraphs) in a linear sequence. These cells can contain code or markdown, but not both in one. This text is an example of a markdown cell. Variables and values are retained until the session is over, so it's important to run all cells. If you skip running a cell then variables may not be initialized and later cells may fail. Also remember to run any cells that have been modified in order for those changes to be available to subsequent cells The cells can be broken into three sections: - **Code editor box**: interactive area to write code - **Output**: displays results under code box - **Cell toolbar**: commands located in the upper right corner of the cell There is also a notebook toolbar located at the top of the notebook. These apply to the entire notebook, for example the run button will execute all cells in the order that they are in within the notebook. A full list of keyboard shortcuts can be found by clicking the List of Shortcuts button (keyboard icon or question mark in a circle) in the upper right corner on the notebook tool bar. Configure cell by clicking the gear button in the upper right corner of the cell. In this, you can change the cell width, move it up or down in order, show title, show line numbers, etc. **Zeppelin Interpreters** Interpreter is a plug-in which allows users to use a specific language/data processing backend. For example, if you want to use python code in Zeppelin then you need the pyspark interpreter. Each interpreter belongs to an InterpreterGroup and these InterpreterGroups can contain multiple interpreters. The InterpreterGoups can be seen by clicking the Interpreter Binding button (gear icon) on the notebook tool bar. For example, you'll find a Spark interpreter group that contains spark, pyspark, SparkSQL, and the dependency loader Looks like: `spark %spark (default), %pyspark, %sql, %dep` Selected interpreters appear in blue. If an interpreter is ever needed that's not in blue, just click on the interpreter name and hit "save" and it will be applied to the notebook you're in. Only one interpreter can be used in each cell, but cells can use different interpreters throughout the notebook to enable multi-language programming. The interpreter needs to be called at the beginning of each cell in the format %[INTERPRETER_NAME], for example if you want to run pyspark then you began the cell with
`%pyspark` **Reporting** Zeppelin is not only for developing and executing code, but also for reporting and visualizing the data analysis workflow. Markdown is a simple syntax used to add formatting to plain-text like headers, bold, and lists. Similar to HTML (HTML can also be used to format texts). In a cell, you can use `%md` at the beginning to call the Markdown interpeter. A helpful guide at getting started with Markdown:
http://markdown-guide.readthedocs.io/en/latest/basics.html#code-block

Run the markdown cell and the output will be a nicely formatted text. You can click on the **'show/hide editor'** button in the upper right of the cell to hide the markdown code and only be left with the output text. For example, click the 'show editor' button to display the hidden markdown code in this cell. **New Notebook** On the homepage of Zeppelin or under the "Notebook" menu, click `Create new note`. You can also click `Import Note` on the home page to import from a URL or a local file.

Reporting

In a cell, you can use %md at the beginning to call the Markdown interpeter. A helpful guide at getting started with Markdown:
http://markdown-guide.readthedocs.io/en/latest/basics.html#code-block

Run the markdown cell and the output will be a nicely formatted text. You can click on the 'show/hide editor' button in the upper right of the cell to hide the markdown code and only be left with the output text. For example, click the 'show editor' button to display the hidden markdown code in this cell.

New Notebook

%md ###Getting Started SparkContext, SQLContext, ZeppelinContext are automatically created and exposed as variable names 'sc', 'sqlContext' and 'z', respectively, both in scala and python environments.
**Important note:** this is exclusive to Zeppelin, if you were to copy your code out of a note and try to run it on the command line then you must remember to implement SparkConf, SparkContext and sqlContext (HiveContext) *Example for Command Line Script:* from pyspark import SparkConf, SparkContext conf = (SparkConf() .setAppName("Spark-Submit: Code Nickname")) sc = SparkContext(conf = conf) from pyspark.sql import HiveContext sqlContext = HiveContext(sc)

result.msg:
Getting Started

SparkContext, SQLContext, ZeppelinContext are automatically created and exposed as variable names 'sc', 'sqlContext' and 'z', respectively, both in scala and python environments.

Important note: this is exclusive to Zeppelin, if you were to copy your code out of a note and try to run it on the command line then you must remember to implement SparkConf, SparkContext and sqlContext (HiveContext)
Example for Command Line Script:

from pyspark import SparkConf, SparkContext
conf = (SparkConf()
        .setAppName("Spark-Submit: Code Nickname"))
sc = SparkContext(conf = conf)

from pyspark.sql import HiveContext
sqlContext = HiveContext(sc)

paragraphs.text:
%pyspark  ##Call interpreter

##Import python packages in the same way you would in python
from sklearn import datasets
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np

# Load iris dataset (sample datasets in scikit-learn)
iris = datasets.load_iris() 

# clean up column names
features = [name[:-5].replace(' ', '_') for name in iris.feature_names]

# read into pandas dataframes
df = pd.DataFrame(iris.data, columns=features)

# create a list of species (150 elements) using iris.target and iris.target_names
species = [iris.target_names[num] for num in iris.target]
species = np.where(iris.target==0, iris.target_names[0],
          np.where(iris.target==1, iris.target_names[1], iris.target_names[2]))

# add the species list as a new DataFrame column
df['species'] = species

# Convert to a Spark dataframe (pandas dataframes cannot be registered as SQL tables)
sdf = sqlContext.createDataFrame(df)

# Registers a dataFrame as a temporary table in the sqlContext to allow for SQL querying
sdf.registerTempTable("temp1")

%md
####To generate built-in visuals, first create a new paragraph and call the SparkSQL interpreter by adding `%sql` at the top. Write a SQL query and run. You'll see a toolbar pop up below the query code with different graphs and charts. When a graph or chart button is clicked, "settings" also appears next to the toolbar. If you click settings, you open up available options.

--The temp table can easily be queried using basic SQL code. Dynamic dropdown/input boxs can also be generated for interactive searches by using a special syntax in a 'where' statement.

SELECT * 
FROM temp1 
where species="${species=setosa,setosa|versicolor|virginica}"
